In [Section 3.1.  Client Registration Request](https://openid.net/specs/openid-connect-registration-1_0.html#RegistrationRequest), it states:

> To register a new Client at the Authorization Server, the Client sends an HTTP POST message to the Client Registration Endpoint with any Client Metadata parameters that the Client chooses to specify for itself during the registration. The Authorization Server assigns this Client a unique Client Identifier, **optionally assigns a Client Secret**

As you noticed, the `clientSecret` is assigned via `CLIENT_SECRET_GENERATOR`, which is the expected behaviour.

If you require dynamic client registration and the `clientSecret` needs to be encoded, a custom configuration is required to meet those requirements.

Here is a sample custom configuration that works:

Replace the `RegisteredClientRepository` `@Bean` defined in `OidcClientRegistrationTests.AuthorizationServerConfiguration` with:

```java
@Bean
RegisteredClientRepository registeredClientRepository(PasswordEncoder passwordEncoder) {
	RegisteredClient registeredClient = TestRegisteredClients.registeredClient()
			.clientSecret(passwordEncoder.encode("secret"))
			.build();
	RegisteredClientRepository delegate = new InMemoryRegisteredClientRepository(registeredClient);

	return new RegisteredClientRepository() {

		@Override
		public void save(RegisteredClient registeredClient) {
			if (StringUtils.hasText(registeredClient.getClientSecret())) {
				RegisteredClient encodedRegisteredClient = RegisteredClient.from(registeredClient)
						.clientSecret(passwordEncoder.encode(registeredClient.getClientSecret()))
						.build();
				delegate.save(encodedRegisteredClient);
			} else {
				delegate.save(registeredClient);
			}
		}

		@Override
		public RegisteredClient findById(String id) {
			return delegate.findById(id);
		}

		@Override
		public RegisteredClient findByClientId(String clientId) {
			return delegate.findByClientId(clientId);
		}

	};
}
```

**NOTE:** The above sample uses `InMemoryRegisteredClientRepository`, but you can use any `RegisteredClientRepository` implementation for this delegation-based pattern.

And replace the `PasswordEncoder` `@Bean` with:

```java
@Bean
PasswordEncoder passwordEncoder() {
	return PasswordEncoderFactories.createDelegatingPasswordEncoder();
}
```

Now run the test `OidcClientRegistrationTests.requestWhenClientRegistrationRequestAuthorizedThenClientRegistrationResponse()` and you will see the `clientSecret` is encoded for the dynamically registered client.

